# 56_actions_path_ops_smoke — Tier 2 m6 Path ops sweep (s255).
# Validates the four wrap-now Path-ops verbs migrated from raw
# `add_action` to `add_scripted_action`: expand-stroke / make-compound
# / split-compound / text-to-path. Sibling smoke to 52 / 53 / 54 / 55,
# same conservative-shape posture.
#
# **Audit discrepancy noted at m6 scoping:** tier2_action_audit.md
# listed FIVE Path-ops verbs (the four above plus `clear`), and the
# Tier 2 wrap-now denominator was set at 49 on that basis. **No
# `win.clear` action exists in the codebase.** A grep for
# `SimpleAction::create("clear"` finds only `m_recents_clear_action`,
# which lives in the `recents` action group, not `win`. No `win.clear`
# action is added anywhere; the only `clear` reachable is
# `recents.clear`. The audit's 5-verb count for Path ops is wrong;
# the real count is 4, and the corrected denominator is 48.
#
# This smoke ships the 4 real verbs. The denominator-correction
# question is surfaced in the m6 wrap-up; whether to amend
# `tier2_action_audit.md` and re-denominator the LEDGER Tier 2 row
# (49 -> 48) is Scott's call at the session close.
#
# **Why conservative.** None of the four path-op verbs has a
# scriptable observable today. expand-stroke / make-compound /
# split-compound / text-to-path all mutate the scene graph — converting
# stroke geometry to filled paths, fusing N paths into one compound,
# exploding a compound back to its children, or converting text glyphs
# to outlined paths. `objects` doesn't expose path-data shape or
# child-count. Trace channel: invocations land cleanly. Visual channel:
# Scott confirms menu items still perform the operations identically.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Seven observables across the wrapper-side surface:
#
#   Phase 1: `list` — confirm `win` is still registered.
#   Phases 2-5: each of the four path-op verbs invoked once.
#   Phases 6-7: refusal coverage.
#
# ── Caller context ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context = RunContext::Scripter.
# All four m6-batch verbs declare Scripter | TestRunner. Macro is OUT.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Mutations to canvas state, applied in order to whatever's selected:
#
#   - `win expand-stroke`   — converts stroked geometry of selection
#                             to filled outline paths. If selection
#                             has no stroke, likely no-op (canvas-side
#                             guard).
#   - `win make-compound`   — fuses N >= 2 selected paths into one
#                             compound path. If selection has < 2 paths,
#                             no-op.
#   - `win split-compound`  — explodes a compound path back to its
#                             constituent children. After phase 3's
#                             make-compound, this likely reverses the
#                             previous step.
#   - `win text-to-path`    — if a text node is selected, converts its
#                             glyphs to outlined paths. Otherwise no-op.
#
# After the smoke runs: depending on initial selection, the canvas
# may have transformed stroke->fill, then fused-then-exploded paths,
# and converted any selected text to paths. Net effect is roughly
# "selection now contains outlined geometry where stroke / text used
# to be." Scott may want ⌘Z multiple times to restore.
#
# Safe to run repeatedly. Not idempotent — text-to-path is irreversible
# at the canvas layer (the text node is replaced by path nodes;
# undoable via the command stack but the second run wouldn't have
# a text node to operate on).
#
# ── Precondition reminders ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke assumes:
#   1. Curvz is running with at least one project + one document open.
#   2. For visual-channel legibility, the document should contain at
#      least: one stroked path (for expand-stroke), two paths selected
#      together (for make-compound's effect), and ideally a text node
#      (for text-to-path's effect). The trace channel passes regardless
#      of canvas content — all four canvas-side handlers guard against
#      bad selection.

#[sub] === Phase 1: registry sanity-check — `win` is still registered ===

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: expand-stroke verb is addressable ===

#[sub] First m6-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.expand_stroke_op(); visual:
#[sub] selection's stroke geometry converts to filled outline paths.

win expand-stroke

#[sub] === Phase 3: make-compound verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Second m6-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.make_compound_path();
#[sub] visual: if N >= 2 paths selected, they fuse into one compound.

win make-compound

#[sub] === Phase 4: split-compound verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Third m6-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.split_compound_path();
#[sub] visual: if a compound is selected, it explodes back to children.
#[sub] After phase 3's make-compound, this likely reverses it.

win split-compound

#[sub] === Phase 5: text-to-path verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fourth and final m6-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.text_to_paths_op();
#[sub] visual: if a text node is selected, its glyphs convert to
#[sub] outlined paths. Otherwise no-op at canvas layer.

win text-to-path

#[sub] === Phase 6: unknown-verb refusal ===

win quit

#[sub] === Phase 7: extra-argument refusal ===

#[sub] Use one of the new m6 verbs for refusal coverage.

win expand-stroke "argument"

